f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates hourly based on the difference between the oracle price and the perpetual contract price, with rates applied every hour rather than the standard 8-hour intervals. The platform uses Chainlink oracles for TAO pricing, which can create temporary arbitrage windows when GMX prices diverge from spot markets. Funding payments are settled directly from the GLP/GM liquidity pools, creating a more predictable funding environment for large positions. The 0.05% maker and 0.07% taker fees must be factored into arbitrage calculations."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","TAO","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TAO's positioning as a premium AI infrastructure play makes it susceptible to funding rate spikes during AI narrative cycles and technical developments in the Bittensor ecosystem. The token's mid-tier volume on GMX creates opportunities for informed traders to capture funding premiums without excessive slippage. Oracle dependency means TAO funding rates on GMX can diverge significantly from CEX rates during high volatility periods."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TAO funding rates on GMX have shown distinct patterns correlating with AI sector momentum and Bittensor network upgrades. During bullish AI narratives, funding rates frequently spike above 0.1% hourly (equivalent to 0.8% daily), creating substantial arbitrage opportunities for short positions. The oracle-based pricing creates smoother funding transitions compared to order book exchanges, with less extreme negative funding during sell-offs. Volatility clustering around subnet launches and TAO token burns has historically provided the most profitable arbitrage windows."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's hourly funding intervals create 3x more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to 8-hour CEX cycles, particularly beneficial for TAO given its volatility profile. Cross-platform arbitrage between GMX and Binance/OKX often yields 10-20 basis points per funding period during network events. The GLP liquidity mechanism means large arbitrage positions can be established without significant market impact, unlike traditional AMMs. Oracle lag during rapid price movements can create temporary mispricings lasting 1-2 funding cycles."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency risk is significant for TAO, as Chainlink price feeds can lag during extreme volatility, potentially resulting in unexpected liquidations. GMX's higher fees (0.05%/0.07%) compared to CEX alternatives require funding rate differentials of at least 15-20 basis points to remain profitable. Arbitrum network congestion during high activity can delay position adjustments, increasing basis risk exposure. The AI sector's narrative-driven volatility means TAO positions can experience rapid sentiment shifts that outpace funding rate adjustments."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are TAO funding rates updated on GMX?","answer":"GMX updates TAO funding rates every hour, providing 24 funding intervals per day compared to 3 on most centralized exchanges. This creates more frequent arbitrage opportunities but requires active monitoring of position exposure."},{"question":"What makes TAO funding different from other AI tokens on GMX?","answer":"TAO's unique positioning in decentralized AI infrastructure creates more volatile funding patterns than generalized AI tokens. Bittensor network events and subnet launches often drive asymmetric funding spikes that don't affect broader AI sector tokens."},{"question":"How does GMX's oracle pricing affect TAO arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Oracle-based pricing reduces manipulation risk but can create lag during rapid TAO price movements. This lag often provides 5-15 minute arbitrage windows when GMX prices haven't updated to reflect spot market moves on major centralized exchanges."},{"question":"What position sizes work best for TAO funding arbitrage on GMX?","answer":"Optimal position sizes are typically $50k-200k for TAO on GMX, balancing meaningful funding capture with manageable liquidation risk. Larger positions may experience slippage during exit, while smaller positions are eroded by the platform's trading fees."}]}]
